      <div xml:id="NA312-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu poruḷ (EV: pirivu) valitta talaimakaṉ neñciṉai neruṅkic colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE who coveted wealth said towards [his] heart.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA312">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nōkō yāṉē nōme ṉeñcē</l>
<l>            paṉipputa līṅkai yaṅkuḻai varuṭac</l>
<l>            ciṟaikuvin tirunta paital veṇkuruku</l>
<l>            pārvai vēṭṭuvaṉ kāḻkaḷain taruḷa</l>
<l>            māri niṉṟa maiya laṟcira</l>
<l>            mayarntaṉa ḷuḻaiya mākavun tāṉē</l>
<l>            yetirtta titti muṟṟā mulaiyaḷ</l>
<l>            kōṭait tiṅkaḷum paṉippōḷ</l>
<l>            vāṭaip perumpaṉik keṉṉaḷko leṉavē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Ah, I ache, aches my heart,</l>
<l>[at the thought]:</l>
<l>what [will become] of her,</l>
<l>because of the great dew [and] the north wind,</l>
<l>she who is shivering [even] in the month of west wind,</l>
<l>she of immature breasts with contrasting beauty spots?</l>
<l>Even when we were near,</l>
<l>she herself became weary</l>
<l>with the maddening(?) cold season arrested in showers,</l>
<l>while the hunter considerately removes the core(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kāḻ kaḷaintu</term>: T.V.G. explains here that the one egret is released by the hunter to serve as decoy for the others. The text being as elusive as it is (and the meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">kāḻ</term> being completely uncertain in this connection), it might as well be that the hunter did not go for the egrets - putting away his arrow? - which would be better in accordance with <term xml:lang="ta">aruḷa</term>.</note> upon seeing</l>
<l>the suffering white egret that was perched, wings fold(?),</l>
<l>as the pretty sprouts of the mimosa in dewy bushes touches [it].</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
